div.h1: Paging Enablement: The Identity-Map Bootstrap Problem

g.text: STEP 1: Kernel Executes No Paging Active
STEP 2: Build Page Tables TWO Mappings Required
STEP 3: Load CR3 with Page Directory Physical Address
STEP 4: Set CR0.PG = 1 Point of No Return
STEP 5: First Instruction Fetch Under Paging Identity Map Saves Us
STEP 6: Far Jump to Higher-Half Virtual Address
STEP 7: Remove Identity Map Now Safe
FAILURE PATH: Step 2 Omits Identity Map

div.p: Color Semantics Red = danger / triple-fault path Green = safe / success path Blue = data flow / memory read Yellow = critical transition Purple = hardware registers Gray = inactive / unused

g.text: Every access is direct physical. No translation. No page tables consulted.
Mapping A: Identity Map (MANDATORY FOR BOOTSTRAP)
MMU now knows where PDEs live. Paging still OFF CR3 loaded but not consulted yet.
mov eax, 0x200000 ; Physical addr of page directory
mov cr3, eax ; Load PDBR paging still OFF
CR0 bit31=PG, bit16=WP. Next instruction fetch goes through MMU. No grace period.
mov cr0, eax: PAGING ENABLED this instruction
Next fetch: CPU computes virt->phys via page tables
mov cr0, eax ; PAGING ACTIVE after this store
TLB caches: virt 0x00100xxx -> phys 0x00100xxx (future hits: 1 cycle)
Identity map saves us kernel continues executing normally
Physical = 0x00100000 -> Same kernel code, different virtual name OK
boot_page_directory[0] = 0 PDE[0] cleared. CR3 reload flushes TLB.
mov cr3, eax ; TLB flush: removes identity entries
DANGER ZONE This is what happens without the identity map
CPU invokes PF handler from IDT[14] at virt 0x00101234
PDE[0] still NOT PRESENT -> PAGE FAULT AGAIN -> DOUBLE FAULT
CPU invokes DF handler from IDT[8] at virt 0x00102000
PDE[0] STILL NOT PRESENT -> Fault again -> TRIPLE FAULT
TRIPLE FAULT: CPU HARD RESET No error message
QEMU: silent reboot. Diagnose with: qemu-system-i386 -d int
WHY: After CR0.PG=1, EIP is still 0x00100xxx. CPU fetches via MMU at virt 0x00100xxx. Without this map: unmapped -> Page Fault -> PF handler also unmapped -> Triple Fault.
WHY: After Step 6 far jump, EIP becomes 0xC0100xxx. Must exist BEFORE that jump or the far jump itself faults.
physical addr mode: safe to write page tables anywhere
both maps written in RAM load CR3
paging ON identity map serves next fetch
still at low virt addr far jump to higher-half
EIP = 0xC01xxxxx safe to remove identity map
IF identity map omitted from Step 2
final physical destination of all kernel fetches
